# 🛡️ Ai-Basesd-Password-Attack-Detection — ML-Powered Login Attack Detection

A Flask web application that uses Machine Learning (Random Forest & Logistic Regression) to detect and block brute-force login attacks in real time.

---

## 📌 Features

- 🔐 Secure login & registration with CSRF protection
- 🤖 Real-time ML-based attack detection (Random Forest model)
- 🚫 Automatic blocking after suspicious activity
- 👮 Admin panel to monitor attacks and manually block/unblock IPs
- 📊 Model comparison dashboard (Random Forest vs Logistic Regression)
- 🧪 Built-in brute-force attack simulator for demo/testing

---

## 🗂️ Project Structure

```
Ai-Basesd-Password-Attack-Detection/
│
├── app.py                  # Main Flask application
├── config.py               # App configuration (secret key, model paths)
├── db.py                   # Database setup and initialization
├── train_model.py          # Script to train and save ML models
├── test_attack.py          # Brute-force attack simulation script
├── requirements.txt        # Python dependencies
│
├── models/                 # Auto-created after training
│   ├── random_forest_model.pkl
│   └── logistic_regression_model.pkl
│
├── templates/
│   ├── layout.html
│   ├── index.html          # Login page
│   ├── register.html
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── admin.html
│   └── model_comparison.html
│
└── static/
    └── css/
        └── style.css
```

---

## ⚙️ Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following installed on your system:

- **Python 3.8 or higher** → [Download Python](https://www.python.org/downloads/)
- **pip** (comes with Python)
- **Git** (to clone the repo)

To check if Python is installed:
```bash
python --version
# or
python3 --version
```

---

## 🚀 Setup & Installation (Step by Step)

### Step 1 — Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/sanjeevan710/Ai-Basesd-Password-Attack-Detection.git
cd ai-shield
```

> Replace `your-username` with your actual GitHub username.

---

### Step 2 — Create a Virtual Environment

A virtual environment keeps dependencies isolated from your system Python.

```bash
# Create the virtual environment
python -m venv venv
```

Activate it:

- **Windows:**
  ```bash
  venv\Scripts\activate
  ```
- **macOS / Linux:**
  ```bash
  source venv/bin/activate
  ```

You should see `(venv)` at the start of your terminal prompt.

---

### Step 3 — Install Dependencies

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

This installs Flask, scikit-learn, pandas, numpy, and all other required packages.

---

### Step 4 — Set Up the Folder Structure

Make sure the `templates/` and `static/css/` directories exist and contain the HTML/CSS files. Your layout should look like this:

```
Ai-Basesd-Password-Attack-Detection/
├── templates/
│   ├── layout.html
│   ├── index.html
│   ├── register.html
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── admin.html
│   └── model_comparison.html
└── static/
    └── css/
        └── style.css
```

If they are missing, create the folders and move the files:

```bash
mkdir -p templates static/css
# Then move your HTML files into templates/ and style.css into static/css/
```

---

### Step 5 — Train the ML Models

This step generates synthetic login data and trains two models, saving them to a `models/` folder.

```bash
python train_model.py
```

Expected output:
```
Generating synthetic dataset...
Training Random Forest...
Random Forest Accuracy: 0.97
Training Logistic Regression...
Logistic Regression Accuracy: 0.XX
Saving models...
Models saved successfully in 'models/' directory.
```

> ⚠️ The app **will not detect attacks** without this step. Always run it before starting the server.

---

### Step 6 — Initialize the Database

The database is auto-created when you first run the app. But you can also initialize it manually:

```bash
python db.py
```

This creates `database.db` with the required tables and a default **admin** account.

---

### Step 7 — Run the Application

```bash
python app.py
```

You should see:
```
✅ Models loaded successfully.
 * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000
```

Open your browser and go to:
```
http://127.0.0.1:5000
```

---

